          "body": "Isaiah 55 stands at the close of chapters 40-55, the section of Isaiah commonly called the Book of Comfort. The unit opens at 40:1 with *Comfort, O comfort My people* and reaches its theological apex in chapter 53 — the Servant who bears the iniquity of many. Chapter 54 then pictures the barren woman (Jerusalem, the people of God) singing because of the Servant's vicarious death. Chapter 55 is the altar call. Everything the Servant purchased in chapter 53 is now extended in chapter 55 as a free invitation. Read in isolation, the chapter sounds like an evangelistic poem; read in context, it is the gospel offer that flows from the cross of Isaiah 53. *Without money and without cost* (55:1) is possible only because the Servant has paid *the chastening for our well-being* (53:5)."
